article.description: Amare Stoudemire scored a career-high 38 points, leading the Phoenix Suns  to a 95-84 victory over the winless New Orleans Hornets on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Hornets tie NBA low with two foul shot attempts
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Hornets hustled back on defense and slowed down the Phoenix Suns' vaunted fast break. If only they could have kept Amare Stoudemire away from the basket. One night after scoring 34 points at Dallas, Stoudemire came back with a career-high 38, leading the Suns to a 95-84 victory over winless New Orleans on Wednesday night. Stoudemire was too strong underneath for any of the Hornets who tried defending him -- be it Jamaal Magloire, P.J. Brown or David West. Stoudemire constantly received the ball in the low post and turned it into easy points, many of them on dunks. Hornets coach Byron Scott was annoyed that his team failed to be physical with Stoudemire early in each possession and keep him farther from the basket. "When you do that to a player like Amare he's going to score and when he doesn't, he's going to get fouled," Scott said. "We didn't push him out, then we were supposed to come down there and double him and he split the double team. We just did a bad job on him -- period." Stoudemire gave much of the credit for his success to Steve Nash, who had 12 assists to go with his 16 points. "With a point guard like Steve the game comes a lot easier for me. He's opened the game for everybody on the team. It's a lot easier and a lot more fun," Stoudemire said. "Sometimes he still surprises me and catches me off guard, but once we get used to each other, it's going to be a heck of a 1-2 punch." Stoudemire also shot 16 more free throws (10-of-18) than the entire New Orleans team. The Hornets' two foul shots tied an NBA low and broke the team mark they set in Milwaukee on Saturday night when they took only three free throws. Cleveland also went to the line just twice against Golden State on Nov. 26, 1994. "Being in this league a long time, when you start losing games and not performing well, referees tend to make everything hard and not give you anything," Brown said. "If we want to get back on track we're going to have to take it. That's just the way it is." Shawn Marion scored 23, including consecutive 3-pointers after the Hornets nibbled a 12-point deficit down to five early in the fourth quarter. David Wesley's 19 points led the Hornets, who are 0-7 under their new coach, the worst start in franchise history. Brown had 12 points and 10 rebounds. The Hornets limited Phoenix to only two baskets in transition. But it hardly mattered with Stoudemire owning the paint, where the Suns scored 50 points. Stoudemire scored 15 in the third quarter alone as the Suns built a lead as large as 12. Joe Johnson's 3-pointer from the right corner made it 63-51. After the Hornets cut the score to 63-56 on a jumper by Brown and a 3 by Darrell Armstrong, Stoudemire again asserted himself inside, grabbing his own rebound after he was blocked by Brown and going back up for a dunk. Stoudemire scored again inside and then hit a pair of free throws to build the Suns' lead back up to 67-56.

Game notes
Hornets G Baron Davis, who missed his second game with an inflamed disc in his lower back, was placed on the injured list, meaning he'll miss at least four more games. ... The Suns led 42-39 at halftime. They've led at the half in all of their games this season. ... Phoenix came in with all five starters averaging double figures in scoring. With Davis out, only two New Orleans starters -- Wesley and Magloire -- were averaging double-digits in scoring. ... Stoudemire has scored at least 20 points in 12 straight games. ... The Suns are 5-1 on the road, their best start in road games since opening 6-1 in 1980-81. The Suns were 11-30 away from home last season.
